{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Diagnostic Tool Selection",
    "objective": "Synthesize the selection of measuring instruments by distinguishing between instantaneous power and cumulative energy in a practical billing scenario.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In a professional setting, you often need to use multiple instruments to solve a single problem. For example, when investigating high running costs, you might need to check the 'push' of the supply, the 'flow' of the current, and the 'rate' of work being done.",
      "However, the most critical distinction for financial reporting is the difference between the power a machine uses at one moment and the total energy it consumes over a working day. One requires a snapshot of the rate, while the other requires a measurement that factors in the passage of time."
    ],
    "questionText": "A technician is investigating why a commercial oven is expensive to run. They use a Wattmeter to see the oven's power demand while it is heating up, but they also need to determine the total cost of running the oven for an entire 8-hour shift. Identify the specific instrument required to measure this 8-hour usage and explain why the Wattmeter alone cannot provide the data needed for the final bill.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The required instrument is an Energy Meter (or kWh meter).",
      "A Wattmeter only measures the instantaneous rate of power (Watts) at a single moment.",
      "An Energy Meter is required because it calculates the cumulative total of power used over a period of time (kilowatt-hours), which is the unit used for billing."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which instrument accounts for 'time' to calculate total consumption rather than just the rate of work 'now'."
  }
}

